					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td width="15">1)</td>
						<td>
						Cut the fresh ginseng into 4cm-long strips. Make holes with needles. Parboil in boiling water with salt. Rinsed in cold water, and drain.
						</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>2)</td>
						<td>
						Put ginseng in a pot and add sugar and water. Boil on a high heat. When it boils up, reduce the heat and simmer without a lid. While boiling, skim the bubbles.
						</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>3)</td>
						<td>
						When sugar water is almost boiled down, add starch syrup and boil until translucent. Add honey and mix up and down. Braise until shiny.
						</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>4)</td>
						<td>
						When finished, pick up and place ginseng on a coarse sieve or net one by one. Cool and serve.
						</td>
					</tr>
